{"text": "Indians began making soaps in the 18th century CE.", "fibs": ["18th"]}
{"text": "Oil of Eranda and seeds of Mahua plant and calcium carbonate were used for making soap.", "fibs": ["plant"]}
{"text": "The paintings found on the walls of Ajanta and Ellora, which look fresh even after ages, testify to a high level of science achieved in ancient India.", "fibs": ["level"]}
{"text": "Varähmihir’s Brihat Samhita is a sort of encyclopaedia, which was composed in the sixth century CE.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "It informs about the preparation of glutinous material to be applied on walls and roofs of houses and temples.", "fibs": ["preparation"]}
{"text": "It will be interesting to test such materials scientifically and assess them for use.", "fibs": ["test"]}
{"text": "A number of classical texts, like Atharvaveda (1000 BCE) mention some dye stuff, the material used were turmeric, madder, sunflower, orpiment, cochineal and lac.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Some other substances having tinting property were kamplcica, pattanga and jatuka.", "fibs": ["tinting"]}
{"text": "Varähmihir’s Brihat Samhita gives references to perfumes and cosmetics.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Recipes for hair dying were made from plants, like indigo and minerals like iron power, black iron or steel and acidic extracts of sour rice gruel.", "fibs": ["hair"]}
{"text": "Gandhayukli describes recipes for making scents, mouth perfumes, bath powders, incense and talcum power.", "fibs": ["mouth"]}
{"text": "Paper was known to India in the17th century as account of Chinese travellerI-tsing describes.", "fibs": ["the17th"]}
{"text": "Excavations at Taxila indicate that ink was used in India from the fourth century.", "fibs": ["ink"]}
{"text": "Colours of ink were made from chalk, red lead and minimum.", "fibs": ["ink"]}
{"text": "It seems that the process of fermentation was well-known to Indians.", "fibs": ["process"]}
{"text": "Vedas and Kautilya’s  Arthashastra mention about many types of liquors.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "Charaka Samhita also mentions ingredients, such as barks of plants, stem, flowers, leaves, woods, cereals, fruits and sugarcane for making Asavas.", "fibs": ["sugarcane"]}
{"text": "The concept that matter is ultimately made of indivisible building blocks, appeared in  India a few centuries BCE as a part of philosophical speculations.", "fibs": ["concept"]}
{"text": "Acharya Kanda, born in 600 BCE, originally known by the name Kashyap, was the first proponent of the ‘atomic theory’.", "fibs": ["name"]}
{"text": "He formulated the theory of very small indivisible particles, which he named ‘Paramãnu’ (comparable to atoms).", "fibs": ["theory"]}
