{"text": "Reference Standard
After defining a unit of measurement such as the kilogram or the metre, scientists agreed on reference standards that make it possible to calibrate all measuring devices.", "fibs": ["unit"]}
{"text": "For getting reliable measurements, all devices such as metre sticks and analytical balances have been calibrated by their manufacturers to give correct readings.", "fibs": ["metre"]}
{"text": "However, each of these devices is standardised or calibrated against some reference.", "fibs": ["reference"]}
{"text": "The mass standard is the kilogram since 1889.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "It has been defined as the mass of platinum-iridium (Pt-Ir) cylinder that is stored in an airtight jar at International Bureau of Weights and Measures in Sevres, France.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "Pt-Ir was chosen for this standard because it is highly resistant to chemical attack and its mass will not change for an extremely long time.", "fibs": ["chemical"]}
{"text": "Scientists are in search of a new standard for mass.", "fibs": ["search"]}
{"text": "This is being attempted through accurate determination of Avogadro constant.", "fibs": ["determination"]}
{"text": "Work on this new standard focuses on ways to measure accurately the number of atoms in a well-defined mass of sample.", "fibs": ["Work"]}
{"text": "One such method, which uses X-rays to determine the atomic density of a crystal of ultrapure silicon, has an accuracy of about 1 part in 106  but has not yet been adopted to serve as a standard.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "There are other methods but none of them are presently adequate to replace the Pt-Ir cylinder.", "fibs": ["none"]}
{"text": "No doubt, changes are expected within this decade.", "fibs": ["doubt"]}
{"text": "The metre was originally defined as the length between two marks on a Pt-Ir bar kept at a temperature of 0°C (273.15 K).", "fibs": ["metre"]}
{"text": "In 1960 the length of the metre was defined as 1.65076373 × 106 times the wavelength of light emitted by a krypton laser.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "Although this was a cumbersome number, it preserved the length of the metre at its agreed value.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The metre was redefined in 1983 by CGPM as the length of path travelled by light in vacuum during a time interval of 1/299 792 458 of a second.", "fibs": ["metre"]}
{"text": "Similar to the length and the mass, there are reference standards for other physical quantities.", "fibs": ["length"]}
{"text": "1.4	Uncertainty in Measurement
Many a time in the study of chemistry, one has to deal with experimental data as well as theoretical calculations.", "fibs": ["Uncertainty"]}
{"text": "There are meaningful ways to handle the numbers conveniently and present the data realistically with certainty to the extent possible.", "fibs": ["certainty"]}
{"text": "These ideas are discussed below in detail.", "fibs": ["detail"]}
{"text": "1.4.1	Scientific Notation
As chemistry is the study of atoms and molecules, which have extremely low masses and are present in extremely large numbers,  a chemist has to deal with numbers as large as 602, 200,000,000,000,000,000,000 for the molecules of 2 g of hydrogen gas or as small as 0.00000000000000000000000166 g mass of a H atom.", "fibs": ["chemistry"]}
{"text": "Similarly, other constants such as Planck’s constant, speed of light, charges on particles, etc., involve numbers of the above magnitude.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "It may look funny for a moment to write or count numbers involving so many zeros but it offers a real challenge to do simple mathematical operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication or division with such numbers.", "fibs": ["moment"]}
{"text": "You can write any two numbers of the above type and try any one of the operations you like to accept as a challenge, and then, you will really appreciate the difficulty in handling such numbers.", "fibs": ["type"]}
{"text": "This problem is solved by using scientific notation for such numbers, i.e., exponential notation in which any number can be represented in the form N × 10n, where n is an exponent having positive or negative values and N is a number (called digit term) which varies between 1.000... and 9.999....", "fibs": ["problem"]}
{"text": "Thus, we can write 232.508 as 2.32508 ×102 in scientific notation.", "fibs": ["×102"]}
{"text": "Note that while writing it, the decimal had to be moved to the left by two places and same is the exponent (2) of 10 in the scientific notation.", "fibs": ["decimal"]}
{"text": "Similarly, 0.00016 can be written as 1.6 × 10–4.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "Here, the decimal has to be moved four places to the right and (–4) is the exponent in the scientific notation.", "fibs": ["decimal"]}
{"text": "While performing mathematical operations on numbers expressed in scientific notations, the following points are to be kept in mind.", "fibs": ["mind"]}
{"text": "Multiplication and Division
These two operations follow the same rules which are there for exponential numbers, i.e.", "fibs": ["Multiplication"]}
{"text": "Addition and Subtraction 
For these two operations, first the numbers are written in such a way that they have the same exponent.", "fibs": ["Addition"]}
{"text": "After that, the coefficients (digit terms) are added or subtracted as the casemay be.", "fibs": ["digit"]}
{"text": "Thus, for  adding  6.65 × 104  and  8.95 × 103, exponent is made same for both the numbers.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "Thus, we get (6.65 × 104) + (0.895 × 104)
Then, these numbers can be added as follows  (6.65 + 0.895) × 104 = 7.545 × 104
Similarly, the subtraction of two numbers can be done as shown below:
(2.5 ×  10–2 ) – (4.8 × 10–3)
	= (2.5 × 10–2) – (0.48 × 10–2) 
	= (2.5 – 0.48) × 10–2 = 2.02 × 10–2
1.4.2	Significant Figures
Every experimental measurement has some amount of uncertainty associated with it because of limitation of measuring instrument and the skill of the person making the measurement.", "fibs": ["×"]}
{"text": "For example, mass of an object is obtained using a platform balance and it comes out to be 9.4g.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "On measuring the mass of this object on an analytical balance, the  mass obtained is 9.4213g.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "The mass obtained by an analytical balance is slightly higher than the mass obtained by using a platform balance.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "Therefore, digit 4 placed after decimal in the measurement by platform balance is uncertain.", "fibs": ["digit"]}
{"text": "The uncertainty in the experimental or the calculated values is indicated by mentioning the number of significant figures.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "Significant figures are meaningful digits which are known with certainty plus one which is estimated or uncertain.", "fibs": ["certainty"]}
{"text": "The uncertainty is indicated by writing the certain digits and the last uncertain digit.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "Thus, if we write a result as 11.2 mL, we say the 11 is certain and 2 is uncertain and the uncertainty would be +1 in the last digit.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "Unless otherwise stated, an uncertainty of +1 in the last digit is always understood.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "There are certain rules for determining the number of significant figures.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "For example in 285 cm, there are three significant figures and in 0.25 mL, there are two significant figures.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "(2)	Zeros preceding to first non-zero digit are not significant.", "fibs": ["digit"]}
{"text": "Such zero indicates the position of decimal point.", "fibs": ["position"]}
{"text": "Thus, 0.03 has one significant figure and 0.0052 has two significant figures.", "fibs": ["figure"]}
{"text": "(4)	Zeros at the end or right of a number are significant, provided they are on the right side of the decimal point.", "fibs": ["end"]}
{"text": "For example, 0.200 g has three significant figures.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "But, if otherwise, the terminal zeros are not significant if there is no decimal point.", "fibs": ["terminal"]}
{"text": "For example, 100 has only one significant figure, but 100. has three significant figures and 100.0 has four significant figures.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Such numbers are better represented in scientific notation.", "fibs": ["notation"]}
{"text": "We can express the number 100 as 1×102 for one significant figure, 1.0×102 for two significant figures and 1.00×102 for three significant figures.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "(5)	Counting the numbers of object, for example, 2 balls or 20 eggs, have infinite significant figures as these are exact numbers and can be  represented by writing infinite number of zeros after placing a decimal i.e.,  2 = 2.000000 or 20 = 20.000000.", "fibs": ["object"]}
{"text": "In numbers written in scientific notation, all digits are significant e.g., 4.01×102 has three significant figures, and 8.256 × 10–3 has four significant figures.", "fibs": ["notation"]}
{"text": "Precision and accuracy are often referred to while we talk about the measurement.", "fibs": ["accuracy"]}
{"text": "Precision refers to the closeness of various measurements for the same quantity.", "fibs": ["closeness"]}
{"text": "However, accuracy is the agreement of a particular value to the true value of the result.", "fibs": ["accuracy"]}
{"text": "For example, if the true value for a result is 2.00 g and student ‘A’ takes two measurements and reports the results as 1.95 g and 1.93 g. These values are precise as they are close to each other but are not accurate.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Another student ‘B’ repeats the experiment and obtains 1.94 g and 2.05 g as the results for two measurements.", "fibs": ["student"]}
{"text": "When the third student ‘C’ repeats these measurements and reports 2.01 g and 1.99 g as the result, these values are both precise and accurate.", "fibs": ["student"]}
{"text": "This can be more clearly understood from the data given in Table 1.4.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
