After about 50 years, in 1860, the first international conference on chemistry was held in Karlsruhe, Germany, to resolve various ideas.", "fibs": ["hydrogen"]}
{"text": "At the meeting, Stanislao Cannizaro presented a sketch of a course of chemical philosophy, which emphasised on the importance of Avogadro’s work.", "fibs": ["meeting"]}
{"text": "John Dalton
(1776–1884)



1.6	Dalton’s Atomic Theory
Although the origin of the idea that matter is composed of small indivisible particles called ‘a-tomio’ (meaning, indivisible), dates back to the time of Democritus, a Greek Philosopher (460–370 BC), it again started emerging as a result of several experimental studies which led to the laws mentioned above.", "fibs": ["1776–1884"]}
{"text": "In 1808, Dalton published ‘A New System of Chemical Philosophy’, in which he proposed the following :
1.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "Matter consists of indivisible atoms.", "fibs": ["Matter"]}
{"text": "All atoms of a given element have identical properties, including identical mass.", "fibs": ["element"]}
{"text": "Atoms of different elements differ in mass.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "Compounds are formed when atoms of different elements combine in a fixed ratio.", "fibs": ["ratio"]}
{"text": "Chemical reactions involve reorganisation of atoms.", "fibs": ["reorganisation"]}
{"text": "These are neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction.", "fibs": ["chemical"]}
{"text": "Dalton’s theory could explain the laws of chemical combination.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "It could not provide the reason for combining of atoms, which was answered later by other scientists.", "fibs": ["reason"]}
{"text": "1.7	Atomic and Molecular Masses
After having some idea about the terms atoms and molecules, it is appropriate here to understand what do we mean by atomic and molecular masses.", "fibs": ["idea"]}
{"text": "1.7.1	Atomic Mass 
The atomic mass or the mass of an atom is actually very-very small because atoms are extremely small.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "Today, we have sophisticated techniques e.g., mass spectrometry for determining the atomic masses fairly accurately.", "fibs": ["Today"]}
{"text": "But in the nineteenth century, scientists could determine the mass of one atom relative to another by experimental means, as has been mentioned earlier.", "fibs": ["century"]}
{"text": "Hydrogen, being the lightest atom was arbitrarily assigned a mass of 1 (without any units) and other  elements were assigned masses relative to it.", "fibs": ["Hydrogen"]}
{"text": "However, the present system of atomic masses is based on carbon-12 as the standard and has been agreed upon in 1961.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "Here, Carbon-12 is one of the isotopes of carbon and can be represented as 12C.", "fibs": ["carbon"]}
{"text": "In this system, 12C is assigned a mass of exactly 12 atomic mass unit (amu) and masses of all other atoms are given relative to this standard.", "fibs": ["system"]}
{"text": "One atomic mass unit is defined as a mass exactly equal to one-twelfth of the mass of one carbon - 12 atom.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "And 1 amu = 1.66056×10–24 g
Mass of an atom of hydrogen 	                                           = 1.6736×10–24 g
Thus, in terms of amu, the mass 
of hydrogen atom  = 
                                = 1.0078 amu 
                                = 1.0080 amu
Similarly, the mass of oxygen - 16 (16O) atom would be 15.995 amu.", "fibs": ["amu"]}
{"text": "At present, ‘amu’ has been replaced by ‘u’, which is known as unified mass.", "fibs": ["‘"]}
{"text": "When we use atomic masses of elements in calculations, we actually use average atomic masses of elements, which are explained below.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "1.7.2	Average Atomic Mass
Many naturally occurring elements exist as more than one isotope.", "fibs": ["isotope"]}
{"text": "When we take into account the existence of these isotopes and their relative abundance (per cent occurrence), the average atomic mass of that element can be computed.", "fibs": ["account"]}
{"text": "For example,  carbon has the following three isotopes with relative abundances and masses as shown against each of them.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "From the above data, the average atomic mass of carbon will come out to be:
(0.98892) (12 u) + (0.01108) (13.00335 u) + (2 × 10–12) (14.00317 u) = 12.011 u
Similarly, average atomic masses for other elements can be calculated.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "In the periodic table of elements, the atomic masses mentioned for different elements actually represent their average atomic masses.", "fibs": ["table"]}
{"text": "1.7.3	Molecular Mass
Molecular mass is the sum of atomic masses of the elements present in a molecule.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "It is obtained by multiplying the atomic mass of each element by the number of its atoms and adding them together.", "fibs": ["mass"]}
{"text": "For example, molecular mass of methane, which contains one carbon atom and four hydrogen atoms, can be obtained as follows:
Molecular mass of methane,  
(CH4) = (12.011 u) + 4 (1.008 u) 
= 16.043 u
Similarly, molecular mass of water (H2O)
= 2 × atomic mass of hydrogen + 1 × atomic 	mass of oxygen
= 2 (1.008 u) + 16.00 u
= 18.02 u
