{"text": "1.10	 Stoichiometry and      		 Stoichiometric Calculations
The word ‘stoichiometry’ is derived from two Greek words — stoicheion (meaning, element) and metron (meaning, measure).", "fibs": ["word"]}
{"text": "Stoichiometry,  thus, deals with the calculation of masses (sometimes volumes also) of the reactants and the products involved in a chemical reaction.", "fibs": ["calculation"]}
{"text": "Before understanding how to calculate the amounts of reactants required or the products produced in a chemical reaction, let us study what information is available from the balanced chemical equation of a given reaction.", "fibs": ["understanding"]}
{"text": "Let us consider the combustion of methane.", "fibs": ["combustion"]}
{"text": "A balanced equation for this reaction is as given below:
CH4 (g) + 2O2 (g) → CO2 (g) + 2 H2O (g)
Here, methane and dioxygen are called reactants and carbon dioxide and water are called products.", "fibs": ["equation"]}
{"text": "Note  that all the reactants and the products are gases in the above reaction and this has been indicated by letter (g) in the brackets next to its formula.", "fibs": ["reaction"]}
{"text": "Similarly, in case of solids and liquids, (s) and (l) are written respectively.", "fibs": ["case"]}
{"text": "The coefficients 2 for O2 and H2O are called stoichiometric coefficients.", "fibs": ["stoichiometric"]}
{"text": "Similarly the coefficient for CH4 and CO2 is one in each case.", "fibs": ["coefficient"]}
{"text": "They represent the number of molecules (and moles as well) taking part in the reaction or formed in the reaction.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "Thus, according to the above chemical reaction,
•	One mole of CH4(g) reacts with two moles of O2(g) to give one mole of CO2(g) and two moles of H2O(g)
•	One molecule of CH4(g) reacts with 2 molecules of O2(g) to give one molecule of CO2(g) and 2 molecules of H2O(g)
•	22.7 L of CH4(g) reacts with 45.4 L of O2 (g) to give 22.7 L of CO2 (g) and 45.4 L of H2O(g)
•	16 g of CH4 (g) reacts with 2×32 g of O2 (g) to give 44 g of CO2 (g) and 2×18 g of  H2O (g).", "fibs": ["chemical"]}
{"text": "From these relationships, the given data can be interconverted as follows:


1.10.1	Limiting Reagent
Many a time, reactions are carried out with the amounts of reactants that are different than the amounts as required by a balanced chemical reaction.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "In such situations, one reactant is in more amount than the amount required by balanced chemical reaction.", "fibs": ["reactant"]}
{"text": "The reactant which is present in the least amount gets consumed after sometime and after that further reaction does not take place whatever be the amount of the other reactant.", "fibs": ["reactant"]}
{"text": "Hence, the reactant, which gets consumed first, limits the amount of product formed and is, therefore, called the limiting reagent.", "fibs": ["reactant"]}
{"text": "In performing stoichiometric calculations, this aspect is also to be kept in mind.", "fibs": ["stoichiometric"]}
